                Chad --



                Sorry we had no time to visit in Dayton.  The event was goo=
d, despite the heat.



                The release of the BJN paper has been a remarkable success.=
  Eric Sorensen did a masterful job, as always, and has been pleasantly sur=
prised by the extent of coverage.  Nic did a great job developing the mater=
ial on the website, the blog has gotten lots of attention, and I am sure th=
ere will be some interesting, further ramifications.



                I attach an accounting of the media thus far =97 370,000,00=
0 circulation of media outlets covering the study, about 1/3 in the UK and =
Europe.  The total reach of the PLOS ONE milk paper, 7 months after release=
, is 420 million, so this one will top it by a wide margin.  There are many=
, many stories still to come in weekly/monthly magazines, more radio, and w=
ho knows what else.  All in all, the coverage was good.  The bickering over=
 antioxidants was to be expected, but I think we responded to it well.



                The cross-Atlantic cooperation was excellent, and everyone =
is looking forward to round 2 when the animal product meta-analysis comes o=
ut late this year, early next year.  We are going to the same journal, and =
are adding papers through the end of 2013 =97 so that includes our PLOS ONE=
 milk paper.



                On the $$ front, we have been turned down on the first two =
NIFA proposals =97 BRAG/alfalfa (expected) and organic transitions/dairy (o=
ur best shot, only medium priority; 2 excellent reviews, one weird one).  H=
ave two more proposals pending, one with the NOP and one with the RWJF.  Di=
sappointing outcome thus far.  Based on the reaction to the AFRI proposals,=
 I really doubt there is much chance for my kind of work to get funding via=
 AFRI.  I could be a bit player in a bigger grant lead by others, but I do =
not see the panels ever considering the sort of work M2M does as important =
as the lab and applied field work they support.  I do think we will have su=
ccess with foundations in the next few years, and that is where I intend to=
 focus in the next 6 months.



                The short-term budget crunch is subsiding.  The $35k from T=
OC/OTA to work on pesticide residues is in, or soon will be (they addressed=
 the check wrong the first time).  The Ceres $$ is in, or soon will be, but=
 I have to discuss an alternative budget with them.  Once that is done, and=
 successfully I hope, we are ok for almost 24 months at current spending =
=97 but me on 1/2 time/pay has to end well before that.



                I am pretty sure the core funders are all in for a third ye=
ar.  I am, however, growing more and more concerned about whether I can rai=
se the $$ to make this program grow.  Nic is great and a huge asset, but M2=
M needs 3-4 PhD level people to meaningful do what we set out to do.  I don=
't see how we get from here to there without one big grant that does not re=
quire a ton of work to raise/manage.  I have no idea where such $$ might co=
me from, but I still think Gates is one of the most likely places.



